Barrington finished second behind Hoffman, and everyone executed their race plans. Good to see things come together and learn from the past
The pack finished with a 15 second split, showing their team work and spirit. This kind of race makes the weeks up to conference stressful..
Mahoney broke away from the pack with 800m to go to show his finishing speed he's been looking for all season...Dude's got some wheels
Then followed the largest pack running I've seen all year: Mahoney, Haufschild, Herrmann, Coombs, Tilly, Susol, King, Stu, and Shinn.
Z got caught in-between Barrington packs, and unfortunately ran by himself for most of the course but still had a great race and raced well.
Laning and Scott ran together for most of the race, slowly picking off targets one-by-one until Laning surged forward in the last half mile
Broncos went up against the top-ranked-in-sectional @HEHSXCTF and Schaumburg. While HE definitely showed their skill, B gained some ground.
Now, with the way varsity ran today, 2015 will be a great year, as well.
May sound like a broken record, but the F/S boys have given the team something to look forward to - a strong 2016-2018 years.
Renetzky also progressed strongly as well, showing us one of his best races of the season, and not too far off the lead packs, either.
Another great show of team work involved Pokorny, Bergman, Giampa, and Lyon, who were able to track down their opponents and surge ahead.
Sorenson took on the slightly short course in 10:15, followed a few seconds later by Old Greg. These two worked together the whole race
F/S started off strong tonight. Shocker. With King moving up to the Varsity race and DeWeerdt out with an injury, the boys still dominated

Overall it was a solid day with some good performances, but the Broncos have a lot of work to do before conference in a few weekends.
Coombs, Haufschild, and Herrmann did well in the open race, followed by Shinn who was much closer to the lead pack than usual.
Jrs. Tilly, Bart, and Stu rounded out V. Though not entirely happy with their race performances, they will be the ones to watch next yr
Laning led the team, followed by Z, Williams, and Sophomore Connor Mahoney, who had his first varsity race today.
Unfortunately, Varsity struggled hard today, but definitely used this race as a learning tool and showed how important team running is
Sophomores had a solid race in a tough field. Missing a couple top guys, they still did well, though their normal aggression wasn't present
Fr. DeWeerdt nabbed 2nd for the team, followed by the always improving Justin Andrews. Sorenson closed in shortly behind him
No surprise the sophomore race was led by King, who ran 7th fastest for the team overall today showing how bad he wants that post season
The guys finished with a 33-second split, which is very rare for this level. Well done fellas.
Few other guys rounded the 7, including Bergman, Lyon, Giampa, and moat surprisingly Reaume, who was nearly speechless after his race
Old Greg lead the race and finished 11th, followed by a HUGE step up by Pokorny in 16th, described as "Running next to Jesus" lol
Coach Root decided to run DeWeerdt in the sophomore race, leaving our top freshman out of this race. Shows how deep the freshman are
Broncos young squad had yet another great day at the Palatine Invitational, finishing second place in a field of 20

Based on Frosh/Soph's performance at Peoria and Argo, the future is looking quite bright for Barrington xc.
Sorenson and Deweerdt had the best team running today running side by side the entire race and finishing in 16:46 and 16:47 respectively.
Aidan King pr-ed today by 37 seconds, getting a 16:40 and placing himself just outside the top seven.
Mahoney proved to be a strong contender in the late season by being our fourth runner overall today.
Immediately after the varsity race, Frosh/Soph toed the line where Laning led the way for Barrington, finishing in a 15:56.
Barrington's aggression, coupled with their team running, proved to be strong factors in their performance today.
The next runners, Stew, Bart, Tilly, and Thomas, had strong pack running and all finished around 16:30.
In the varsity meet, Scott led the way with a 15:45 followed closely by z with a 15:56.
Barrington not only had a successful day in argo, but also down in Peoria with a p-r by every runner.
